[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":2248},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":2224,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2023\u002F05\u002F13\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types\u002F":2233},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20230513\u002F284079926\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":17,"date":2208,"description":2209,"extension":2210,"lang":2211,"meta":2212,"navigation":613,"path":2213,"readingMinutes":2214,"seo":2215,"standalone":2216,"stem":2217,"tags":2218,"tldr":2221,"updated":2208,"url":2222,"__hash__":2223},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fcant-use-typescript-write-jsdoc-types.md","Can't Use TypeScript? Don't Worry — You Can Still Annotate Types With JSDoc","1001536289",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":2191},"minimark",[11,19,24,27,31,34,37,40,50,54,62,88,95,101,104,108,111,170,177,183,186,191,202,290,297,302,305,312,402,407,418,504,510,523,629,632,636,643,712,715,721,724,730,765,769,776,781,822,827,830,836,840,888,894,898,946,952,956,1015,1020,1023,1028,1032,1116,1119,1249,1254,1257,1263,1266,1377,1382,1389,1498,1502,1516,1568,1574,1802,1805,1811,1824,1880,1883,2040,2057,2111,2115,2118,2160,2169,2173,2176,2184,2187],[12,13,14],"p",{},[15,16],"img",{"alt":17,"src":18},"JavaScript","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fn4QxX62.png",[20,21,23],"h2",{"id":22},"intro","Intro",[12,25,26],{},"If your company's project can't use TypeScript but you still want something like TypeScript's type checking, give JSDoc a try. With JSDoc you can annotate types and get checks that feel a lot like TypeScript.",[20,28,30],{"id":29},"whats-jsdoc","What's JSDoc?",[12,32,33],{},"Let's start with what JSDoc actually is. JSDoc stands for \"JavaScript Documentation\" — it's a tool built specifically for documenting JavaScript.",[12,35,36],{},"So what can it do? Basically it helps you annotate things: types, parameters, return values, and so on. Before TypeScript existed, JSDoc was a really handy tool — and honestly it was good enough to get the job done.",[12,38,39],{},"So let's take a look at how to use it. Before we start though, a quick note about my IDE — I'm using Visual Studio Code, the best IDE on the planet (in my humble opinion), and its JSDoc support is excellent. So all my examples here are in VSCode.",[41,42,43],"blockquote",{},[12,44,45,49],{},[46,47,48],"strong",{},"Note","\nJSDoc has been around for a long time — since roughly 1999 — so it actually predates TypeScript.",[20,51,53],{"id":52},"setup","Setup",[12,55,56,57,61],{},"First, create a project in VSCode called ",[58,59,60],"code",{},"jsdoc-demo"," and initialize npm inside it:",[63,64,69],"pre",{"className":65,"code":66,"language":67,"meta":68,"style":68},"language-bash shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","npm init -y\n","bash","",[58,70,71],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,73,76,80,84],"span",{"class":74,"line":75},"line",1,[72,77,79],{"class":78},"s_sBn","npm",[72,81,83],{"class":82},"sTRMh"," init",[72,85,87],{"class":86},"sCcAr"," -y\n",[12,89,90,91,94],{},"Then create an ",[58,92,93],{},"index.js"," file. Your project structure should look like this:",[12,96,97],{},[15,98],{"alt":99,"src":100},"init","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fv73vEgs.png",[12,102,103],{},"Once that's ready, let's keep going.",[20,105,107],{"id":106},"how-to-write-jsdoc","How to Write JSDoc",[12,109,110],{},"Writing JSDoc isn't hard. Here's a bit of example code to start with:",[63,112,116],{"className":113,"code":114,"language":115,"meta":68,"style":68},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","const sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n","js",[58,117,118,147,164],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,119,120,124,128,131,135,138,141,144],{"class":74,"line":75},[72,121,123],{"class":122},"sWyjQ","const",[72,125,127],{"class":126},"sj_SG"," sayHi",[72,129,130],{"class":122}," =",[72,132,134],{"class":133},"sMAXC"," (",[72,136,137],{"class":78},"name",[72,139,140],{"class":133},") ",[72,142,143],{"class":122},"=>",[72,145,146],{"class":133}," {\n",[72,148,150,153,156,158,161],{"class":74,"line":149},2,[72,151,152],{"class":122},"  return",[72,154,155],{"class":82}," `Hi, ${",[72,157,137],{"class":133},[72,159,160],{"class":82},"}`",[72,162,163],{"class":133},";\n",[72,165,167],{"class":74,"line":166},3,[72,168,169],{"class":133},"};\n",[12,171,172,173,176],{},"So how do you annotate it? You just type ",[58,174,175],{},"\u002F**"," above the function, and our mighty VSCode will suggest a JSDoc comment for you:",[12,178,179],{},[15,180],{"alt":181,"src":182},"JSDoc comment","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FKPLD9M6.png",[12,184,185],{},"Hit Enter and it'll auto-generate the JSDoc comment, like this:",[12,187,188],{},[15,189],{"alt":181,"src":190},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FUN5U3wr.png",[12,192,193,194,197,198,201],{},"Pretty convenient, right? You can see VSCode generated ",[58,195,196],{},"@param {*} name"," and ",[58,199,200],{},"@returns"," for us. So how do we fill these in? It's simple — usually we describe what the function does, the type of each parameter, and the type of the return value. So you'd write it like this:",[63,203,205],{"className":113,"code":204,"language":115,"meta":68,"style":68},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n",[58,206,207,213,218,235,247,253,272,285],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,208,209],{"class":74,"line":75},[72,210,212],{"class":211},"sQrFR","\u002F**\n",[72,214,215],{"class":74,"line":149},[72,216,217],{"class":211}," * Greeting function\n",[72,219,220,223,226,229,232],{"class":74,"line":166},[72,221,222],{"class":211}," * ",[72,224,225],{"class":122},"@param",[72,227,228],{"class":78}," { string }",[72,230,231],{"class":133}," name",[72,233,234],{"class":211}," The name\n",[72,236,238,240,242,244],{"class":74,"line":237},4,[72,239,222],{"class":211},[72,241,200],{"class":122},[72,243,228],{"class":78},[72,245,246],{"class":211}," Hi, ${name}\n",[72,248,250],{"class":74,"line":249},5,[72,251,252],{"class":211}," *\u002F\n",[72,254,256,258,260,262,264,266,268,270],{"class":74,"line":255},6,[72,257,123],{"class":122},[72,259,127],{"class":126},[72,261,130],{"class":122},[72,263,134],{"class":133},[72,265,137],{"class":78},[72,267,140],{"class":133},[72,269,143],{"class":122},[72,271,146],{"class":133},[72,273,275,277,279,281,283],{"class":74,"line":274},7,[72,276,152],{"class":122},[72,278,155],{"class":82},[72,280,137],{"class":133},[72,282,160],{"class":82},[72,284,163],{"class":133},[72,286,288],{"class":74,"line":287},8,[72,289,169],{"class":133},[12,291,292,293,296],{},"Now when you hover your mouse over ",[58,294,295],{},"sayHi",", a tooltip shows up:",[12,298,299],{},[15,300],{"alt":295,"src":301},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fz88Ygca.png",[12,303,304],{},"So whenever you use this function somewhere else, JSDoc reminds you what it does, what parameter types it expects, and what it returns. That saves you a ton of time digging through the function to figure out what it's for, what to pass in, and what comes back.",[12,306,307,308,311],{},"JSDoc doesn't stop there, though. You can also use ",[58,309,310],{},"@example"," to show how the function is used:",[63,313,315],{"className":113,"code":314,"language":115,"meta":68,"style":68},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n * @example\n * sayHi('John'); \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n",[58,316,317,321,325,337,347,354,362,366,384,397],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,318,319],{"class":74,"line":75},[72,320,212],{"class":211},[72,322,323],{"class":74,"line":149},[72,324,217],{"class":211},[72,326,327,329,331,333,335],{"class":74,"line":166},[72,328,222],{"class":211},[72,330,225],{"class":122},[72,332,228],{"class":78},[72,334,231],{"class":133},[72,336,234],{"class":211},[72,338,339,341,343,345],{"class":74,"line":237},[72,340,222],{"class":211},[72,342,200],{"class":122},[72,344,228],{"class":78},[72,346,246],{"class":211},[72,348,349,351],{"class":74,"line":249},[72,350,222],{"class":211},[72,352,353],{"class":122},"@example\n",[72,355,356,359],{"class":74,"line":255},[72,357,358],{"class":211}," * sayHi('John');",[72,360,361],{"class":211}," \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n",[72,363,364],{"class":74,"line":274},[72,365,252],{"class":211},[72,367,368,370,372,374,376,378,380,382],{"class":74,"line":287},[72,369,123],{"class":122},[72,371,127],{"class":126},[72,373,130],{"class":122},[72,375,134],{"class":133},[72,377,137],{"class":78},[72,379,140],{"class":133},[72,381,143],{"class":122},[72,383,146],{"class":133},[72,385,387,389,391,393,395],{"class":74,"line":386},9,[72,388,152],{"class":122},[72,390,155],{"class":82},[72,392,137],{"class":133},[72,394,160],{"class":82},[72,396,163],{"class":133},[72,398,400],{"class":74,"line":399},10,[72,401,169],{"class":133},[12,403,404],{},[15,405],{"alt":310,"src":406},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fj5EkcBH.png",[12,408,409,410,413,414,417],{},"What if a parameter can accept multiple types — say ",[58,411,412],{},"string"," or ",[58,415,416],{},"number","? You can write it like this:",[63,419,421],{"className":113,"code":420,"language":115,"meta":68,"style":68},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string | number } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n * @example\n * sayHi('John'); \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n",[58,422,423,427,431,444,454,460,466,470,488,500],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,424,425],{"class":74,"line":75},[72,426,212],{"class":211},[72,428,429],{"class":74,"line":149},[72,430,217],{"class":211},[72,432,433,435,437,440,442],{"class":74,"line":166},[72,434,222],{"class":211},[72,436,225],{"class":122},[72,438,439],{"class":78}," { string | number }",[72,441,231],{"class":133},[72,443,234],{"class":211},[72,445,446,448,450,452],{"class":74,"line":237},[72,447,222],{"class":211},[72,449,200],{"class":122},[72,451,228],{"class":78},[72,453,246],{"class":211},[72,455,456,458],{"class":74,"line":249},[72,457,222],{"class":211},[72,459,353],{"class":122},[72,461,462,464],{"class":74,"line":255},[72,463,358],{"class":211},[72,465,361],{"class":211},[72,467,468],{"class":74,"line":274},[72,469,252],{"class":211},[72,471,472,474,476,478,480,482,484,486],{"class":74,"line":287},[72,473,123],{"class":122},[72,475,127],{"class":126},[72,477,130],{"class":122},[72,479,134],{"class":133},[72,481,137],{"class":78},[72,483,140],{"class":133},[72,485,143],{"class":122},[72,487,146],{"class":133},[72,489,490,492,494,496,498],{"class":74,"line":386},[72,491,152],{"class":122},[72,493,155],{"class":82},[72,495,137],{"class":133},[72,497,160],{"class":82},[72,499,163],{"class":133},[72,501,502],{"class":74,"line":399},[72,503,169],{"class":133},[12,505,506],{},[15,507],{"alt":508,"src":509},"type","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FgLjGZ5d.png",[12,511,512,513,516,517,519,520,522],{},"Here's something worth pointing out. Why do I say JSDoc is a solid choice when you can't use TypeScript? From the examples above, JSDoc clearly helps us out. But that alone is far from enough — because developers are human. You might've already written ",[58,514,515],{},"@param { string } name"," for ",[58,518,295],{},", and yet still accidentally pass a ",[58,521,416],{}," when calling it:",[63,524,526],{"className":113,"code":525,"language":115,"meta":68,"style":68},"\u002F**\n * Greeting function\n * @param { string } name The name\n * @returns { string } Hi, ${name}\n * @example\n * sayHi('John'); \u002F\u002F Hi, John\n *\u002F\nconst sayHi = (name) => {\n  return `Hi, ${name}`;\n};\n\nsayHi(1);\n",[58,527,528,532,536,548,558,564,570,574,592,604,608,615],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,529,530],{"class":74,"line":75},[72,531,212],{"class":211},[72,533,534],{"class":74,"line":149},[72,535,217],{"class":211},[72,537,538,540,542,544,546],{"class":74,"line":166},[72,539,222],{"class":211},[72,541,225],{"class":122},[72,543,228],{"class":78},[72,545,231],{"class":133},[72,547,234],{"class":211},[72,549,550,552,554,556],{"class":74,"line":237},[72,551,222],{"class":211},[72,553,200],{"class":122},[72,555,228],{"class":78},[72,557,246],{"class":211},[72,559,560,562],{"class":74,"line":249},[72,561,222],{"class":211},[72,563,353],{"class":122},[72,565,566,568],{"class":74,"line":255},[72,567,358],{"class":211},[72,569,361],{"class":211},[72,571,572],{"class":74,"line":274},[72,573,252],{"class":211},[72,575,576,578,580,582,584,586,588,590],{"class":74,"line":287},[72,577,123],{"class":122},[72,579,127],{"class":126},[72,581,130],{"class":122},[72,583,134],{"class":133},[72,585,137],{"class":78},[72,587,140],{"class":133},[72,589,143],{"class":122},[72,591,146],{"class":133},[72,593,594,596,598,600,602],{"class":74,"line":386},[72,595,152],{"class":122},[72,597,155],{"class":82},[72,599,137],{"class":133},[72,601,160],{"class":82},[72,603,163],{"class":133},[72,605,606],{"class":74,"line":399},[72,607,169],{"class":133},[72,609,611],{"class":74,"line":610},11,[72,612,614],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":613},true,"\n",[72,616,618,620,623,626],{"class":74,"line":617},12,[72,619,295],{"class":126},[72,621,622],{"class":133},"(",[72,624,625],{"class":86},"1",[72,627,628],{"class":133},");\n",[12,630,631],{},"That'll cause a problem, and for us devs it's an easy way to introduce bugs. So are we stuck just biting the bullet and using TypeScript? Nope — JSDoc can do type validation too. We just haven't set up our environment for it yet. So let's do that.",[20,633,635],{"id":634},"jsdoc-type-checking-and-autocomplete","JSDoc Type Checking and Autocomplete",[12,637,638,639,642],{},"First, create a ",[58,640,641],{},"jsconfig.json"," file in the project root with this content:",[63,644,648],{"className":645,"code":646,"language":647,"meta":68,"style":68},"language-json shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","{\n  \"compilerOptions\": {\n    \"checkJs\": true,\n    \"allowJs\": true\n  },\n  \"exclude\": [\"node_modules\"]\n}\n","json",[58,649,650,655,664,678,688,693,707],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,651,652],{"class":74,"line":75},[72,653,654],{"class":133},"{\n",[72,656,657,661],{"class":74,"line":149},[72,658,660],{"class":659},"sKpQp","  \"compilerOptions\"",[72,662,663],{"class":133},": {\n",[72,665,666,669,672,675],{"class":74,"line":166},[72,667,668],{"class":659},"    \"checkJs\"",[72,670,671],{"class":133},": ",[72,673,674],{"class":86},"true",[72,676,677],{"class":133},",\n",[72,679,680,683,685],{"class":74,"line":237},[72,681,682],{"class":659},"    \"allowJs\"",[72,684,671],{"class":133},[72,686,687],{"class":86},"true\n",[72,689,690],{"class":74,"line":249},[72,691,692],{"class":133},"  },\n",[72,694,695,698,701,704],{"class":74,"line":255},[72,696,697],{"class":659},"  \"exclude\"",[72,699,700],{"class":133},": [",[72,702,703],{"class":82},"\"node_modules\"",[72,705,706],{"class":133},"]\n",[72,708,709],{"class":74,"line":274},[72,710,711],{"class":133},"}\n",[12,713,714],{},"Now you should see error messages:",[12,716,717],{},[15,718],{"alt":719,"src":720},"JSDoc type validation","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FOhNxREP.png",[12,722,723],{},"And if you don't pass the parameter correctly, you'll get a warning too:",[12,725,726],{},[15,727],{"alt":728,"src":729},"JSDoc parameter validation","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fqt8lXbb.png",[12,731,732,733,735,736,738,739,742,743,745,746,748,749,752,753,756,757,764],{},"If you're a TypeScript developer, ",[58,734,641],{}," probably looks familiar — that's because ",[58,737,641],{}," is derived from ",[58,740,741],{},"tsconfig.json",". So you can use ",[58,744,741],{}," settings inside ",[58,747,641],{},", like ",[58,750,751],{},"\"target\": \"es6\"",", ",[58,754,755],{},"\"module\": \"commonjs\"",", and so on. I won't go deep into those here, but if you want to learn more, check the ",[758,759,763],"a",{"href":760,"rel":761},"https:\u002F\u002Fcode.visualstudio.com\u002Fdocs\u002Flanguages\u002Fjsconfig",[762],"nofollow","official docs",".",[20,766,768],{"id":767},"other-jsdoc-patterns","Other JSDoc Patterns",[12,770,771,772,775],{},"Now that we've covered the basics of writing JSDoc and the basic setup, let's talk about some other patterns. In real-world dev things are never this simple — you'll be dealing with arrays and objects too. So let's start with a plain variable declaration. If you want to put a type on a variable, there's a new piece of JSDoc syntax for that: ",[58,773,774],{},"@type",". Here are a few examples.",[777,778,780],"h3",{"id":779},"variable-declaration","Variable Declaration",[63,782,784],{"className":113,"code":783,"language":115,"meta":68,"style":68},"\u002F**\n * My name\n * @type { string }\n *\u002F\nconst myName = 'Ray';\n",[58,785,786,790,795,804,808],{"__ignoreMap":68},[72,787,788],{"class":74,"line":75},[72,789,212],{"class":211},[72,791,792],{"class":74,"line":149},[72,793,794],{"class":211}," * My name\n",[72,796,797,799,801],{"class":74,"line":166},[72,798,222],{"class":211},[72,800,774],{"class":122},[72,802,803],{"class":78}," { string }\n",[72,805,806],{"class":74,"line":237},[72,807,252],{"class":211},[72,809,810,812,815,817,820],{"class":74,"line":249},[72,811,123],{"class":122},[72,813,814],{"class":86}," myName",[72,816,130],{"class":122},[72,818,819],{"class":82}," 'Ray'",[72,821,163],{"class":133},[12,823,824],{},[15,825],{"alt":508,"src":826},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FZ9542SQ.png",[12,828,829],{},"By defining the variable's type, autocomplete works corr